{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17628650","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17628650"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T16:59:07+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T16:59:07+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17230"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17230","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17230"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9920"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"77393"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9920","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9920"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17230"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"62900"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4940"},{"type":"tags","id":"4945"},{"type":"tags","id":"7615"},{"type":"tags","id":"7620"},{"type":"tags","id":"10749"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"23262"},{"type":"contributions","id":"23267"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"77393","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/77393"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EHistone modifications can either facilitate or restrict access of transcriptional machinery to DNA.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the effect of histone acetylation on gene expression?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Represses gene expression by condensing chromatin","Prevents DNA replication during cell division","Promotes gene expression by loosening chromatin structure","Promotes DNA methylation patterns","Recruits DNA repair enzymes to damaged sites"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHistone acetylation promotes gene expression by loosening chromatin structure\u003C/strong\u003E. When acetyl groups are added to histone tails, they neutralise the positive charge of lysine residues, reducing the interaction between histones and negatively charged DNA. This results in a more open chromatin structure that allows better access for transcription factors and RNA polymerase.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERepressing gene expression by condensing chromatin\u003C/strong\u003E - This is the effect of histone deacetylation, not acetylation\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPreventing DNA replication during cell division\u003C/strong\u003E - Histone acetylation does not directly prevent DNA replication\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPromoting DNA methylation patterns\u003C/strong\u003E - While histone modifications and DNA methylation can work together, acetylation does not directly promote methylation\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERecruiting DNA repair enzymes to damaged sites\u003C/strong\u003E - While some histone modifications are involved in DNA repair, this is not the primary function of histone acetylation\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHistone acetylation is a reversible modification catalysed by histone acetyltransferases (HATs), while histone deacetylases (HDACs) remove acetyl groups. This dynamic process helps regulate gene expression without changing the DNA sequence.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Histone acetylation generally promotes gene expression by loosening chromatin structure and increasing DNA accessibility.","Histone deacetylation generally represses gene expression by promoting compact chromatin structure.","Histone modifications are reversible epigenetic changes that do not alter DNA sequence."],"references":["Turnpenny PD, Ellard S. Emery\u0027s Elements of Medical Genetics E-Book: Elsevier Health Sciences; 2011","Bannister AJ, Kouzarides T. Regulation of chromatin by histone modifications. Cell Research. 2011;21(3):381-95. Available at: https://www.nature.com/articles/cr201122"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"62900"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17230"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"62900","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/62900"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-06T21:28:53+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-06T23:57:53+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9920"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"77393"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data"